= La selva se lo traga

The army took the Colonia Rubén Jaramillo back in the end, as everyone always knew it would — occupied it, renamed it, assigned it the forgetting that is the state's most patient weapon. Medrano refused the moral of that story. He went south with a handful of the irreducibles, into the Oaxaca and Veracruz lowlands, to organize the poorest Mexicans there are: jungle colonos, coffee pickers, people the Republic's maps mark as vegetation.

Word of his death arrives the way everything arrives from down there — late, disputed, and in several versions. An ambush; a firefight; a wound that traveled faster than the man. What is agreed: the Güero is gone, in the green dark, far from the hillside city he built and lost, still holding the surveyor's chain.

The colonias of the Valle hold his wake without a body. It lasts three nights, which in colonia arithmetic is a head of state.

- @heredar: Inherit the method: the colonia work continues under his name, which no eviction order can serve papers on.

@heredar
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: sup_colonos += 3; colonia_presion += 1; political_capital += 1

The manuals he left — hand-drawn, mimeographed, practical as recipes — circulate through the coordinadoras with his nickname on the cover. Every invasion that follows the method is, in the only sense that matters to him now, his. The state can occupy a hillside. The knowledge of how hillsides are taken has no address to occupy.
